    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks, that helps a lot. Some of my students are asking if there are other ways to look at the 14th Amendment, like if it's just about following proper legal procedures (procedural due process) rather than the actual content of the laws. How would you respond to them? Is that a valid way to look at it, or does that approach kind of miss the real point of why the amendment exists?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It is absolutely valid to discuss procedural due process, as it addresses the *how* of the law—ensuring fair play in legal proceedings, like providing notice before taking someone's property. However, focusing *only* on procedure misses the radical protective core of the 14th Amendment. Substantive due process tackles the *what* of the law—the actual content—asking whether the government is even allowed to infringe on fundamental rights in the first place. Together, the two concepts provide a complete framework for protecting liberty, but substantive due process is what challenges unjust laws themselves.",
      "source": "target",
